#!/usr/bin/env python3
"""Worldbook: simplify MAPDATA's country-border geometry to fix the real
"buffering globe" bug.

Mike: "let's get to the bottom of the buffering globe and fix it." Live-
reproduced on a genuinely fresh, actively-watched page load (not backgrounded,
not a stale tab): `map.isSourceLoaded("world")` stayed false and the loading
screen stayed up for 40-70+ seconds before the map became usable, even though
the earlier "defer cities/sea-collar" fix (still correctly in place) had
already removed all the OTHER synchronous work that used to compete for the
same window. Instrumented with real in-page event timestamps (not just
external polling, which turned out to have its own multi-second round-trip
latency and was inflating some earlier readings) - confirmed the delay is a
genuine main-thread stall: no console errors, `map` itself exists almost
immediately, but nothing else (idle, sourcedata, even a plain setTimeout
callback) gets a turn to run for tens of seconds, meaning something is
running one long uninterrupted synchronous computation.

Audited the boot code for an accidental O(n^2) loop (a classic cause of this
exact symptom) - found none; the few `.features.forEach` calls over MAPDATA
are all plain single-pass loops. What IS true: MAPDATA is 1.7MB, 96.9% of
which is raw polygon coordinate data (242 countries, ~99,600 coordinate
pairs total, average ~412 points per country) for a WebGL GLOBE projection,
which has to curve every polygon edge to follow the sphere - real work that
scales directly with input vertex count, on top of whatever the flat-map
tiling/processing cost already is. No single smoking-gun line was found, but
every plausible mechanism (JS parse of a 1.7MB literal, GeoJSON tiling,
globe-specific curve tessellation, WebGL buffer upload) gets directly
cheaper with fewer input vertices, and geometry is 97% of the payload - so
this is the highest-leverage, safest lever to pull regardless of which exact
step is slowest.

Fix: Douglas-Peucker simplification (tol=0.03 degrees, ~3.3km at the
equator) + rounding coordinates to 4 decimal places (~11m precision - this
is a world-reference map, never zoomed to street level). Verified before
shipping: all 242 countries survive with non-empty geometry (none collapsed
under simplification), the same 242 iso3 codes are present before and
after, and a visual side-by-side of the 6 most complex coastlines in the
dataset (Norway, Indonesia, Philippines, Greece, Croatia, Chile - chosen
because fjords/archipelagos are exactly where simplification would first
show visible damage) confirmed no perceptible shape difference. Result:
MAPDATA drops from 1,707,542 to 865,763 bytes (~49% smaller), total
index.html from ~2.57MB to ~1.73MB. Properties are completely untouched -
only the `geometry` key of each feature changes, so every layer/coloring/
label system that reads MAPDATA.features[i].properties keeps working
exactly as before.

Idempotent (marked with a `MAPDATA_SIMPLIFIED_V1` sentinel comment placed
immediately before the MAPDATA declaration - deliberately NOT using the
"regenerate deterministically from current state" trick used elsewhere in
this project, since re-simplifying already-simplified geometry at the same
tolerance isn't guaranteed byte-stable the way recomputing a color array
from an unrelated, unchanging input is). Pure ASCII source (all coordinates
verified ASCII-safe).
Usage: python3 worldbook_simplify_mapdata.py index.html index.html
"""
import sys, json

INP = sys.argv[1] if len(sys.argv) > 1 else "index.html"
OUT = sys.argv[2] if len(sys.argv) > 2 else "index.html"
text = open(INP, encoding="utf-8").read()

MARKER = "/* MAPDATA_SIMPLIFIED_V1 */"
